                        HEDIT v1.04 User Manual
                   CP/M 2.2 Hex Editor for the IMSAI 8080
                   =======================================


    1. INTRODUCTION

    HEDIT is a full-screen hex editor for CP/M 2.2.  It provides hex
    and ASCII editing of binary files and Intel HEX files, block
    operations, search, and configurable key bindings.

    HEDIT is distributed as five variants, one per supported terminal
    family.  Pick the binary that matches your terminal:

      HEDIT.COM     VT100 / ANSI, mono
      HEDIT-CL.COM  VT100 / ANSI, colour
      HEDIT-52.COM  DEC VT52 and clones (Heath H19, Soroc IQ-120,
                    Televideo 912/920, etc.)
      HEDIT-AD.COM  Lear Siegler ADM-31
      HEDIT-CR.COM  Cromemco 3102 / Beehive DM10 / DM30

    All five variants share the same editing commands and on-screen
    layout.  They differ only in the escape sequences they emit and,
    for some, the arrow-key decoding.

    Requirements:
      - CP/M 2.2 or compatible
      - A terminal matching one of the five variants above
      - Minimum 9 KB free TPA


    2. STARTING HEDIT

    From the CP/M prompt:

      A>HEDIT                    Start with empty buffer
      A>HEDIT MYFILE.COM         Open MYFILE.COM for editing
      A>HEDIT B:DATA.HEX         Open Intel HEX file on drive B:

    Substitute HEDIT-CL, HEDIT-52, HEDIT-AD or HEDIT-CR for other
    variants.  You may want to rename the variant you use most often
    to HEDIT.COM so it can be started with just "HEDIT".

    When started without a filename, the info bar shows [No Name].
    You will be prompted for a filename when you save.


    3. SCREEN LAYOUT

    Row 1:       Info bar       filename, file size, cursor offset,
                                mode flags
    Row 2:       Column header
    Rows 3..N-2: Hex data area  (N-4 rows x 16 bytes each)
    Row N-1:     Separator line (version string + '=' fill)
    Row N:       Status / message bar

    N is the terminal's row count.  On a 24-row VT100 the hex area
    fills rows 3..22 (20 rows, 320 bytes visible).  The VT100 builds
    query the terminal at startup via DSR (Device Status Report) and
    grow the hex area to fit up to 76 rows.  The VT52, ADM-31 and
    Cromemco 3102 builds are fixed at 24 rows because those protocols
    do not support DSR.

    Each data row displays:

      XXXX: HH HH HH HH HH HH HH HH  HH HH HH HH HH HH HH HH  ASCII text here.

      XXXX   = hex address (0000-FFFF)
      HH     = hex byte values
      ASCII  = printable characters (20h-7Eh), others shown as '.'

    The info bar shows:
      Filename  Size:XXXX  Off:XXXX  [INS]/[OVR]  [HEX]/[ASC]  [BIN]/[IHEX]


    4. EDITING MODES

    HEX mode (default):
      The cursor is in the hex field.  Type 0-9 and A-F to enter byte
      values.  Two keystrokes complete one byte (high nibble, then low
      nibble).  Lowercase a-f are accepted.

    ASCII mode (press Tab to toggle):
      The cursor moves to the ASCII field.  Type any printable character
      (space through '~') to enter its byte value directly.

    Insert mode (press Ins or ^V to toggle):
      New bytes are inserted at the cursor position, shifting existing
      data to the right.  The info bar shows [INS].

    Overwrite mode (default):
      Existing bytes are replaced in place.  The info bar shows [OVR].


    5. NAVIGATION

    Key              Action
    ---              ------
    Up arrow / ^E    Move up 16 bytes (one row)
    Down arrow / ^X  Move down 16 bytes (one row)
    Left arrow / ^S  Move left 1 byte
    Right arrow / ^D Move right 1 byte
    PgUp / ^R        Move up one page (one screenful)
    PgDn / ^C        Move down one page (one screenful)
    Home / ^QS       Move to start of current row
    End / ^QD        Move to end of current row
    ^QR              Move to top of file
    ^QC              Move to end of file

    Page size scales with the terminal: 320 bytes on a 24-row
    terminal, more on a taller one (for example 576 bytes on 40 rows).


    ARROW KEYS BY TERMINAL

    On VT100 and VT52 terminals, the arrow keys send their usual
    escape sequences and work directly in HEDIT.

    On ADM-31 and Cromemco 3102, the arrow keys transmit raw control
    characters that collide with HEDIT's WordStar bindings:

      Up arrow    = ^K  (starts the WordStar block prefix)
      Down arrow  = ^J  (no mapping, silently ignored)
      Left arrow  = ^H  (mapped to Backspace / Delete Left)
      Right arrow = ^L  (mapped to Find Next)

    On those terminals use the WordStar diamond for cursor motion:

      ^E = up     ^X = down    ^S = left    ^D = right
      ^R = page up            ^C = page down

    The Cromemco 3102 build additionally accepts VT100-style arrow
    escape sequences (ESC [ A/B/C/D), so a Cromemco 3102 emulator
    driven by a PC keyboard will just work.


    6. EDITING KEYS

    Key              Action
    ---              ------
    0-9, A-F         Hex byte input (HEX mode)
    Printable char   ASCII byte input (ASCII mode)
    Tab / ^I         Toggle HEX/ASCII mode
    Ins / ^V         Toggle Insert/Overwrite mode
    Backspace / ^H   Delete byte to the left
    Del / ^G         Delete byte to the right
    ^Y               Delete row (16 bytes at cursor)


    7. BLOCK OPERATIONS

    ^KB or F3        Set block mark (start or end)
                     First press marks the start.  Move the cursor to
                     the desired end position.  Selected bytes are shown
                     in reverse video as you move.  Second press sets
                     the end of the block.  Third press clears the mark.

    ^KC or ^O        Copy marked block to clipboard
    ^KD              Delete marked block
    ^KP              Paste clipboard at cursor position

    The clipboard holds up to 2048 bytes.

    On VT52 (strict DEC) and terminals without reverse video, the
    highlight is not visible but the mark state is still tracked.


    8. SEARCH

    ^L or F1         Find next (repeats last search)
    Menu -> Find     Start a new search

    When starting a search:
      1. Choose (H)ex or (A)SCII mode (press H or A, ESC to cancel)
      2. Enter the search pattern:
         - Hex mode: enter byte values like "4D 5A 90" (spaces optional,
           lowercase accepted and auto-uppercased)
         - ASCII mode: enter text like "Hello"
      3. Press Enter to search, ESC to cancel

    The search wraps around if the pattern is not found forward.
    "Found." or "Not found." is shown on the status bar.


    9. FILE OPERATIONS

    ^KS or F2        Save file (quick save)
    ESC              Open menu

    Save creates a .BAK backup of the previous version before writing.

    File formats:
      Binary (BIN):   Raw bytes saved directly.
      Intel HEX:      Standard Intel HEX format with checksums.

    Format is auto-detected on load (files starting with ':' are
    Intel HEX).  Use Menu -> Toggle Format to change before saving.


    10. INTEL HEX FILES

    When loading an Intel HEX file:
      - The base address from the first data record is preserved
      - The gutter and info bar show the actual HEX addresses
      - Address gaps between records are filled with FFh bytes
      - Type 02/04 extended address records are not supported
        (an error is shown and they are skipped)

    When saving as Intel HEX:
      - Data records use 16-byte lines with correct checksums
      - The base address is included in record addresses
      - An EOF record is appended

    To set the base address manually:
      Menu -> Base Offset -> enter high byte (00-FF)
      This sets the starting address to XX00h.


    11. ESC MENU

    Press ESC or F4 to open the menu.  Navigate with:
      - Arrow keys (Up/Down) and Enter to select
      - Number keys 1-9, 0 for direct selection
      - Shortcut letter (shown in bold on VT100, plain text on other
        terminals)

    Menu items:
      1. [O]pen File         Open a new file
      2. [S]ave File         Save current file
      3. Save [A]s...        Save with a new filename
      4. [F]ind              Search for hex bytes or ASCII text
      5. [G]o To Offset      Jump to a hex address
      6. [H]elp / About      Show key reference and version
      7. [B]ase Offset       Set Intel HEX base address
      8. [T]oggle Format     Switch between Binary and Intel HEX
      9. Fi[l]l Block...     Fill a range with a byte value
      0. E[x]it              Exit (prompts to save if modified)

    Press ESC or Q to close the menu without selecting.


    12. EXITING

    ESC -> Exit (or press 0 or X in the menu)

    If the buffer has been modified, HEDIT asks:
      "Save changes? (Y/N/Esc)"
      Y = save and exit (prompts for filename if unnamed)
      N = discard changes and exit
      Esc = cancel, return to editor


    13. KEY BINDING FILE (HEDIT.KEY)

    HEDIT supports customizable key bindings through an optional
    HEDIT.KEY file.  If present on the current drive, it is read
    at startup and used to remap control keys and escape sequences
    to editor actions.


    14. REBUILDING FROM SOURCE ON CP/M

    Every variant ships with a SUBMIT file that rebuilds it from the
    source tree in-place:

      SUBMIT HEDIT      build HEDIT.COM    (VT100 mono)
      SUBMIT HEDIT-CL   build HEDIT-CL.COM (VT100 colour)
      SUBMIT HEDIT-52   build HEDIT-52.COM (VT52)
      SUBMIT HEDIT-AD   build HEDIT-AD.COM (ADM-31)
      SUBMIT HEDIT-CR   build HEDIT-CR.COM (Cromemco 3102)

    Each .SUB is self-contained: it rebuilds HEPATCH.COM, runs it to
    set the COLOR flag in HECONFIG.INC, clears *.REL, assembles every
    required module with M80, links to TEMP.COM, then renames TEMP.COM
    to the target filename.  A fresh floppy with just the source files
    and the M80 / L80 / SUBMIT toolchain can produce any variant.

    Housekeeping:

      SUBMIT CLEAN      remove *.REL and TEMP.COM
      SUBMIT HEPATCH    rebuild just HEPATCH.COM


    15. LIMITATIONS

    - Maximum file size is limited by available TPA memory
    - Addresses are 16-bit (0000h-FFFFh)
    - Intel HEX extended address records (Type 02/04) are not supported
    - Clipboard maximum is 2048 bytes
    - Search pattern maximum is 64 bytes
    - Terminal auto-sizing (DETSIZ) is available only on the VT100
      builds; VT52, ADM-31 and Cromemco 3102 builds are fixed at 24 rows
